{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f64d5f43-60ca-4a68-bf75-5fcc444b0829","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates these:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`. They contain the stack trace, exception type, and faulting address.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check under **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a user-friendly view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — These are disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file appears at `/tmp/core.<pid>` and can be loaded with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp -c /tmp/core.12345\n   ```\n\n**Start with `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — it's the easiest path and requires no setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da1b1545-a52e-4fd3-a8c1-4d6b1766f8ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":315,"requestId":"980C:18FEB2:593885A:61B959C:69F40684"},"id":"98214619-a2f1-4357-a2db-8ad934444fc4","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:49:00.987Z","parentId":"ae245d22-9f00-4654-93f2-d70f6b46ca37"}
